{
  "answer": "**'The Seafarer' is chapter 5 of *Old English Elegies*.**[^1]\n\nNothing in the poem specifically links \"flesh\" and \"worms.\" The term \"flesh-home\" (a compound for the body) appears once, describing how it becomes inert after death: \"Nor can his flesh-home, when the life has fled, / taste any sweetness or feel any sorrow, / nor stir a hand, nor think with his heart.\"[^2] This reflects on the transience of earthly life and the futility of worldly wealth, as the body cannot enjoy burial treasures.[^2]\n\n\"Worms\" do appear elsewhere in *Old English Elegies* (chapter 10, *Soul and Body II*), where the soul addresses the corpse: \"Listen, you food for worms\" and \"many mound-worms shall chew you.\"[^3] But this is a separate elegy, not *The Seafarer*.\n\nThe corpus covers *The Seafarer* fully, with no such combined reference.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, chapter 5 (\"Maey ich be me sylfum...\"), [translation](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, chapter 5, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-4d6f48).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, chapter 10 (\"Soul and Body II\"), paragraphs [p-34bcc7](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-34bcc7) and [p-7f7247](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-7f7247).",
